{"title_page": "Hanna Suchocka", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|name           = Hanna Suchocka\n|image          = [[File:Hanna Suchocka 1135.jpg|220px]]\n|office         = 5th [[Prime Minister of Poland]]\n|president      = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n|deputy         = [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Henryk Goryszewski]]<br>[[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Pawe\u0142 \u0141\u0105czkowski]]\n|term_start     = 8 July 1992\n|term_end       = 26 October 1993\n|predecessor    = [[Waldemar Pawlak]]\n|successor      = [[Waldemar Pawlak]]\n|office1        = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Polish Ambassador to the Sovereign Military Order of Malta]]\n|appointer1     = [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] \n|term_start1    = 10 October 2002\n|term_end1      = 30 June 2013\n|predecessor1   = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Stefan Frankiewicz]]\n|successor1     = [[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]\n|office2        = [[Holy See|Polish Ambassador to the Holy See]]\n|appointer2     = [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] \n|1blankname2       = {{nowrap|Pope}}\n|1namedata2        = [[John Paul II]]<br>[[Benedict XVI]]<br>[[Pope Francis|Francis]]\n|term_start2    = 3 December 2001\n|term_end2      = 30 June 2013\n|predecessor2   = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Stefan Frankiewicz]]\n|successor2     = [[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]\n|office3        = [[Ministry of Justice (Poland)|Minister of Justice]]<br>[[Public Prosecutor General (Poland)|Public Prosecutor General]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Jerzy Buzek]]\n|term_start3    = 31 October 1997\n|term_end3      = 8 June 2000\n|predecessor3   = [[Leszek Kubicki]]\n|successor3     = [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]]\n|office4        = First Vice President of the [[Venice Commission]]\n|primeminister4 = \n|term_start4    = 19 December 2015\n|term_end4      = 29 April 2016\n|predecessor4   = [[Jan Erik Helgesen]]\n|successor4     = [[Kaarlo Tuori]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1946|04|03|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Pleszew]], [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Alliance of Democrats (Poland)|Alliance of Democrats]] {{small|(Before 1989)}}<br>[[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] {{small|(1989\u20131990)}}<br>[[Democratic Union (Poland)|Democratic Union]] {{small|(1990\u20131994)}}<br>[[Freedom Union (Poland)|Freedom Union]] {{small|(1994\u20132000)}}\n|alma_mater     = [[Adam Mickiewicz University in Pozna\u0144|University of Pozna\u0144]]<br> {{small|[[PhD]] (1975), [[Habilitation]] (2015)}}\n|occupation     = [[legal scholar]], [[diplomat]]\n|awards         = [[File:POL Order Or\u0142a Bia\u0142ego BAR.svg|40px|Order of the White Eagle (Poland)]] [[File:Order Pius Ribbon 1kl.png|40px|Order of Pius IX]]\n}}\n'''Hanna Suchocka''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8xanna\u00a0su\u02c8x\u0254tska|pron|Pl-Hanna Suchocka.ogg}}; born 3 April 1946) is a [[Poland|Polish]] [[political figure]], [[lawyer]], [[professor]] at [[Adam Mickiewicz University in Pozna\u0144]] and Chair of the Constitutional Law Department, former First Vice-President<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.venice.coe.int/WebForms/pages/default.aspx?p=cv_79&lang=EN|title=Venice Commission :: Council of Europe|website=www.venice.coe.int|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pap.pl/aktualnosci/news,510835,msz-banaszak-i-muszynski-nowymi-czlonkami-komisji-weneckiej.html|title=MSZ: Banaszak i Muszy\u0144ski nowymi cz\u0142onkami Komisji Weneckiej {{!}} Aktualno\u015bci {{!}} Polska Agencja Prasowa|website=www.pap.pl|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> and Honorary President of the [[Venice Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pap.pl/en/news-/news,539541,former-polish-pm-named-honorary-president-of-venice-commission.html|title=Former Polish PM named honorary president of Venice Commission {{!}} News_ {{!}} Polish Press Agency|website=www.pap.pl|access-date=2016-06-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115165240/http://www.pap.pl/en/news-/news,539541,former-polish-pm-named-honorary-president-of-venice-commission.html|archive-date=15 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe served as the [[prime minister of Poland]] between 8 July 1992 and 26 October 1993 under the presidency of [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]. She is the first  woman to hold this post in Poland (with [[Ewa Kopacz]] and [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]] holding the post in the 2010s) and was the 14th woman to be appointed and serve as prime minister in the world.<ref>Skard, Torild (2014) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women of Power - Half a century of female presidents and prime ministers worldwide'', Bristol: Policy Press, {{ISBN|978-1-44731-578-0}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSuchocka was born in [[Pleszew]], Poland, in a Catholic family of chemists. Her grandfather was a University teacher and her grandmother Anna became member of the first Polish parliament after independence in 1918, when women got the right to vote. Suchocka went to law school and became a researcher at the University of Poznan but she was fired when she refused to join the Communist party. She was preoccupied by human rights and undertook a PhD in [[Constitutional Law]] in West Germany in 1975.\n\nIn 1969 she joined a small non-Marxist '[[Bloc party (politics)#Poland|satellite party]]', the [[Alliance of Democrats (Poland)|Democratic Party]] (SD), and was a member of parliament the [[Sejm]] of [[People's Republic of Poland]] in 1980-1985. At the same time she was a member and a legal advisor to ''[[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]]''. She was one of only a few MPs who did not to vote in favour of [[Martial law in Poland|martial law]] in 1981 and the criminalisation of ''Solidarity'' in 1984. The party suspended her (or she resigned), but with the support of ''Solidarity'' she was reelected to parliament in 1989. When Solidarity supporters split up into several political parties, Suchocka joined the centre-liberal [[Democratic Union (Poland)|Democratic Union]] (DU) and was re-elected to parliament in 1991.\n\n==Prime Minister==\nShe became Prime Minister in 1992. Governments at the time were based on various coalitions and changed constantly. Suchocka was chosen to the amazement of many male politicians but she was known for her low profile and willingness to make compromises and promote reconciliation. She could be accepted by people who had antipathy towards more prominent leaders of DU. In addition, as a left-winger, while being opposed to abortion as a Catholic, she could be accepted by both sides of the political spectrum and satisfy the interests of a majority in a parliament consisting of seven parties, including a Christian and a liberal party.<ref>Opfell (1993) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women prime ministers and presidents'', Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co, {{ISBN|978-0899507903}}, pp. 212-22; Skard, Torild (2014) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women of power - Half a century of female presidents and prime ministers worldwide'', Bristol: Policy Press, {{ISBN|978-1-44731-578-0}}, pp. 344-5</ref>\n\nHanna Suchocka declared that her government was for social reconciliation and would lead the country forward in the transformation from communism to capitalism. She was approved by 233 against 61 votes and 113 abstentions<ref>''Current Biography'' 1994, January, New York, NY: H.W.Wilson, pp 50-3</ref> She quickly formed a cabinet, but it didn't include any other female ministers, although she wanted them. None of the coalition partners were willing to accept another woman and she got two male deputy prime ministers. She stayed longer as prime minister than any of her four predecessors, but she did not stay long. There was a wave of strikes and Suchocka was a warm supporter of market reforms and followed a hard line against the strikers. When she wouldn't give salary increases to teachers and health workers, parliament passed a vote of no-confidence by a majority of one vote. Wa\u0142\u0119sa dissolved parliament and held new elections and Suchocka resigned as soon as the new parliament was in place.<ref>Lewis, Jone Johnson (1992) ''Hanna Suchocka government'', October, www.womenshistory.about.com and ''Who's Who in Poland, Directory of members of parliament, state and local government and the presidential chancellery 1994-1995'', (1994) Warsaw, p.II-497</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nIn 1994 Hanna Suchocka was one of the founders of a liberal and social-democratic Liberty Union party, which became the country's third largest political force. From 1997 to 2000 she was the minister of justice in a coalition government.<ref>Siemienska, Renata (2003) \"Women in the Polish Sejm\" in R.E.Matland and K.A.Montgomery (eds) ''Women's access to political power in post-communist Europe'', Oxford/New York, NY: Oxford University Press, pp. 217-44</ref>\n\nShe is also a member of the [[Club of Madrid]].<ref>{{in lang|en}} [http://www.clubmadrid.org The Club of Madrid] is an independent organization dedicated to strengthening democracy around the world by drawing on the unique experience and resources of its Members \u2013 66 democratic former heads of state and government.</ref>\n\nHanna Suchocka is a member of the [[Council of Women World Leaders]], an international network of current and former women presidents and prime ministers whose mission is to mobilize the highest-level women leaders globally for collective action on issues of critical importance to women and equitable development.\n\nShe served as Poland's Ambassador to the [[Holy See]] from 2002 to 2013. She was also a member of the [[Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]] in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] (appointed by [[Pope John Paul II]] on 19 January 1994).\n[[File:Hanna Suchocka, Prime Minister of Poland 1992-1993.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Suchocka as Prime Minister]]\nIn April 2014 Suchocka was among the 8 initial appointees of [[Pope Francis]] to the [[Pontifical Commission for the Protection of Minors]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303802104579455253788559122?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303802104579455253788559122.html ''Wall Street Journal'' March 22, 2014]</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pass.va/content/scienzesociali/en/academicians/former/suchoka.html Suchocka's page at the Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Waldemar Pawlak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=1992\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Waldemar Pawlak]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leszek Kubicki]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (Poland)|Minister of Justice]]|years=1997\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Stefan Frankiewicz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Polish Ambassador to the [[Holy See]]|years=2001\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=Polish Ambassador to the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]]|years=2002\u20132013}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Poland}}\n{{Ministers of Justice of Poland}}\n{{Hanna Suchocka Cabinet}}\n{{Jerzy Buzek Cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suchocka, Hanna}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Democrats (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Democratic Union (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government in Poland]]\n[[Category:Freedom Union (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Justice ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1980\u20131985]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1991\u20131993]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1993\u20131997]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pontifical Commission for the Protection of Minors]]\n[[Category:People from Pleszew]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Sejm of the Polish People's Republic]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Sejm of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Female justice ministers]]\n[[Category:Polish women diplomats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|name           = Hanna Suchocka\n|image          = [[File:Hanna Suchocka 1135.jpg|220px]]\n|office         = 5th [[Prime Minister of Poland]]\n|president      = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n|deputy         = [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Henryk Goryszewski]]<br>[[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Pawe\u0142 \u0141\u0105czkowski]]\n|term_start     = 8 July 1992\n|term_end       = 26 October 1993\n|predecessor    = [[Waldemar Pawlak]]\n|successor      = [[Waldemar Pawlak]]\n|office1        = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Polish Ambassador to the Sovereign Military Order of Malta]]\n|appointer1     = [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] \n|term_start1    = 10 October 2002\n|term_end1      = 30 June 2013\n|predecessor1   = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Stefan Frankiewicz]]\n|successor1     = [[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]\n|office2        = [[Holy See|Polish Ambassador to the Holy See]]\n|appointer2     = [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] \n|1blankname2       = {{nowrap|Pope}}\n|1namedata2        = [[John Paul II]]<br>[[Benedict XVI]]<br>[[Francis]]\n|term_start2    = 3 December 2001\n|term_end2      = 30 June 2013\n|predecessor2   = [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Stefan Frankiewicz]]\n|successor2     = [[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]\n|office3        = [[Ministry of Justice (Poland)|Minister of Justice]]<br>[[Public Prosecutor General (Poland)|Public Prosecutor General]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Jerzy Buzek]]\n|term_start3    = 31 October 1997\n|term_end3      = 8 June 2000\n|predecessor3   = [[Leszek Kubicki]]\n|successor3     = [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]]\n|office4        = First Vice President of the [[Venice Commission]]\n|primeminister4 = \n|term_start4    = 19 December 2015\n|term_end4      = 29 April 2016\n|predecessor4   = [[Jan Erik Helgesen]]\n|successor4     = [[Kaarlo Tuori]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1946|04|03|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Pleszew]], [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Alliance of Democrats (Poland)|Alliance of Democrats]] {{small|(Before 1989)}}<br>[[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] {{small|(1989\u20131990)}}<br>[[Democratic Union (Poland)|Democratic Union]] {{small|(1990\u20131994)}}<br>[[Freedom Union (Poland)|Freedom Union]] {{small|(1994\u20132000)}}\n|alma_mater     = [[Adam Mickiewicz University in Pozna\u0144|University of Pozna\u0144]]<br> {{small|[[PhD]] (1975), [[Habilitation]] (2015)}}\n|occupation     = [[legal scholar]], [[diplomat]]\n|awards         = [[File:POL Order Or\u0142a Bia\u0142ego BAR.svg|40px|Order of the White Eagle (Poland)]] [[File:Order Pius Ribbon 1kl.png|40px|Order of Pius IX]]\n}}\n'''Hanna Suchocka''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8xanna\u00a0su\u02c8x\u0254tska|pron|Pl-Hanna Suchocka.ogg}}; born 3 April 1946) is a [[Poland|Polish]] [[political figure]], [[lawyer]], [[professor]] at [[Adam Mickiewicz University in Pozna\u0144]] and Chair of the Constitutional Law Department, former First Vice-President<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.venice.coe.int/WebForms/pages/default.aspx?p=cv_79&lang=EN|title=Venice Commission :: Council of Europe|website=www.venice.coe.int|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pap.pl/aktualnosci/news,510835,msz-banaszak-i-muszynski-nowymi-czlonkami-komisji-weneckiej.html|title=MSZ: Banaszak i Muszy\u0144ski nowymi cz\u0142onkami Komisji Weneckiej {{!}} Aktualno\u015bci {{!}} Polska Agencja Prasowa|website=www.pap.pl|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> and Honorary President of the [[Venice Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pap.pl/en/news-/news,539541,former-polish-pm-named-honorary-president-of-venice-commission.html|title=Former Polish PM named honorary president of Venice Commission {{!}} News_ {{!}} Polish Press Agency|website=www.pap.pl|access-date=2016-06-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115165240/http://www.pap.pl/en/news-/news,539541,former-polish-pm-named-honorary-president-of-venice-commission.html|archive-date=15 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe served as the [[prime minister of Poland]] between 8 July 1992 and 26 October 1993 under the presidency of [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]. She is the first  woman to hold this post in Poland (with [[Ewa Kopacz]] and [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]] holding the post in the 2010s) and was the 14th woman to be appointed and serve as prime minister in the world.<ref>Skard, Torild (2014) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women of Power - Half a century of female presidents and prime ministers worldwide'', Bristol: Policy Press, {{ISBN|978-1-44731-578-0}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSuchocka was born in [[Pleszew]], Poland, in a Catholic family of chemists. Her grandfather was a University teacher and her grandmother Anna became member of the first Polish parliament after independence in 1918, when women got the right to vote. Suchocka went to law school and became a researcher at the University of Poznan but she was fired when she refused to join the Communist party. She was preoccupied by human rights and undertook a PhD in [[Constitutional Law]] in West Germany in 1975.\n\nIn 1969 she joined a small non-Marxist '[[Bloc party (politics)#Poland|satellite party]]', the [[Alliance of Democrats (Poland)|Democratic Party]] (SD), and was a member of parliament the [[Sejm]] of [[People's Republic of Poland]] in 1980-1985. At the same time she was a member and a legal advisor to ''[[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]]''. She was one of only a few MPs who did not to vote in favour of [[Martial law in Poland|martial law]] in 1981 and the criminalisation of ''Solidarity'' in 1984. The party suspended her (or she resigned), but with the support of ''Solidarity'' she was reelected to parliament in 1989. When Solidarity supporters split up into several political parties, Suchocka joined the centre-liberal [[Democratic Union (Poland)|Democratic Union]] (DU) and was re-elected to parliament in 1991.\n\n==Prime Minister==\nShe became Prime Minister in 1992. Governments at the time were based on various coalitions and changed constantly. Suchocka was chosen to the amazement of many male politicians but she was known for her low profile and willingness to make compromises and promote reconciliation. She could be accepted by people who had antipathy towards more prominent leaders of DU. In addition, as a left-winger, while being opposed to abortion as a Catholic, she could be accepted by both sides of the political spectrum and satisfy the interests of a majority in a parliament consisting of seven parties, including a Christian and a liberal party.<ref>Opfell (1993) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women prime ministers and presidents'', Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co, {{ISBN|978-0899507903}}, pp. 212-22; Skard, Torild (2014) \"Hanna Suchocka\" in ''Women of power - Half a century of female presidents and prime ministers worldwide'', Bristol: Policy Press, {{ISBN|978-1-44731-578-0}}, pp. 344-5</ref>\n\nHanna Suchocka declared that her government was for social reconciliation and would lead the country forward in the transformation from communism to capitalism. She was approved by 233 against 61 votes and 113 abstentions<ref>''Current Biography'' 1994, January, New York, NY: H.W.Wilson, pp 50-3</ref> She quickly formed a cabinet, but it didn't include any other female ministers, although she wanted them. None of the coalition partners were willing to accept another woman and she got two male deputy prime ministers. She stayed longer as prime minister than any of her four predecessors, but she did not stay long. There was a wave of strikes and Suchocka was a warm supporter of market reforms and followed a hard line against the strikers. When she wouldn't give salary increases to teachers and health workers, parliament passed a vote of no-confidence by a majority of one vote. Wa\u0142\u0119sa dissolved parliament and held new elections and Suchocka resigned as soon as the new parliament was in place.<ref>Lewis, Jone Johnson (1992) ''Hanna Suchocka government'', October, www.womenshistory.about.com and ''Who's Who in Poland, Directory of members of parliament, state and local government and the presidential chancellery 1994-1995'', (1994) Warsaw, p.II-497</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nIn 1994 Hanna Suchocka was one of the founders of a liberal and social-democratic Liberty Union party, which became the country's third largest political force. From 1997 to 2000 she was the minister of justice in a coalition government.<ref>Siemienska, Renata (2003) \"Women in the Polish Sejm\" in R.E.Matland and K.A.Montgomery (eds) ''Women's access to political power in post-communist Europe'', Oxford/New York, NY: Oxford University Press, pp. 217-44</ref>\n\nShe is also a member of the [[Club of Madrid]].<ref>{{in lang|en}} [http://www.clubmadrid.org The Club of Madrid] is an independent organization dedicated to strengthening democracy around the world by drawing on the unique experience and resources of its Members \u2013 66 democratic former heads of state and government.</ref>\n\nHanna Suchocka is a member of the [[Council of Women World Leaders]], an international network of current and former women presidents and prime ministers whose mission is to mobilize the highest-level women leaders globally for collective action on issues of critical importance to women and equitable development.\n\nShe served as Poland's Ambassador to the [[Holy See]] from 2002 to 2013. She was also a member of the [[Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]] in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] (appointed by [[Pope John Paul II]] on 19 January 1994).\n[[File:Hanna Suchocka, Prime Minister of Poland 1992-1993.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Suchocka as Prime Minister]]\nIn April 2014 Suchocka was among the 8 initial appointees of [[Pope Francis]] to the [[Pontifical Commission for the Protection of Minors]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303802104579455253788559122?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303802104579455253788559122.html ''Wall Street Journal'' March 22, 2014]</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pass.va/content/scienzesociali/en/academicians/former/suchoka.html Suchocka's page at the Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Waldemar Pawlak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=1992\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Waldemar Pawlak]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leszek Kubicki]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (Poland)|Minister of Justice]]|years=1997\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Stefan Frankiewicz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Polish Ambassador to the [[Holy See]]|years=2001\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Piotr Nowina-Konopka]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=Polish Ambassador to the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]]|years=2002\u20132013}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Poland}}\n{{Ministers of Justice of Poland}}\n{{Hanna Suchocka Cabinet}}\n{{Jerzy Buzek Cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suchocka, Hanna}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Democrats (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Democratic Union (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government in Poland]]\n[[Category:Freedom Union (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Justice ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1980\u20131985]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1991\u20131993]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1993\u20131997]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pontifical Commission for the Protection of Minors]]\n[[Category:People from Pleszew]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Sejm of the Polish People's Republic]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Sejm of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Female justice ministers]]\n[[Category:Polish women diplomats]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toFrancis(link changed toPope Francis) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanna_Suchocka"}
{"title_page": "Indian chess", "text_new": ":''This article is about regional versions of chess played in India. For ancient Indian chess variants, which are believed to be predecessors of chess by some historians, see [[chaturanga]].''\n\n'''Indian chess''' is the name given to a variation of [[chess]] played in [[India]] in the 18th and 19th centuries.  The more ancient forms are known as [[chaturanga]], and spread to the west via [[Persia]] in the 7th Century. There are several such [[Chess variant|variations]], all quite similar to [[rules of chess|modern rules]], with variants regarding [[castling]], [[promotion (chess)|pawn promotion]], etc. These variants were popular in India until the 1960s. However, even today a mix of Indian method and international are used in some parts of India.\n\n== Differences from Western chess ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Expand section|date=July 2010}}\n\n* The [[king (chess)|king]] is always placed to the right of the [[queen (chess)|queen]] (as opposed to the left for Black).\n* King cannot move unless a check is given at least once. \n* When only the king and [[pawn (chess)|pawns]] are left in play, the opponent may not give check, but they can win by stalemate, variants of this include the check being allowed but the capture of last pawn being disallowed (resulting in a draw).\n* The two-step initial pawn move is absent in Indian chess; thus, ''[[en passant]]'' is also absent.\n* Normal castling with rook and king is absent. The king can make a [[knight (chess)|knight's]] move once in a game, known as ''Indian castling''.\n* On reaching the opposite end of the board, pawns [[Promotion (chess)|promote]] to the piece of that square. If it promotes at the initial [[king (chess)|king's]] position, it promotes a [[queen (chess)|queen]].  \n* [[Underpromotion]] is not permitted.\n* The last piece remaining may not be captured, variants include the capture being allowed if the last piece is not a pawn.\n\n==Names of the pieces==\n\nThe following table describes one version of Subcontinental chess terminology for the various pieces (including Hindi and Urdu pronunciations):<ref name=JLC>{{cite web|last1=Cazaux|first1=Jean-Louis|title=Indian Chess Sets|url=http://history.chess.free.fr/india.htm|website=Another view on Chess:  Odyssey of Chess|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! Piece\n!Standard (English)\n! Hindi\n!Urdu\n\n|-\n|King || [[King (chess)|king]] || \u0930\u093e\u091c\u093e ''r\u0101j\u0101'' || \u0628\u0627\u062f\u0634\u0627\u06c1 ''b\u0101dsh\u0101h\n|-\n|Mantri/Vizier/Queen/Senapati || [[Queen (chess)|queen]] || \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 ''mantri'' / \u0935\u091c\u093c\u0940\u0930 ''vaz\u012br'' / \u0930\u093e\u0928\u0940 ''r\u0101n\u012b'' / \u0938\u0947\u0928\u093e\u092a\u0924\u093f ''senapati''||\u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631\u200e ''vaz\u012br'' / \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u0627 ''malka''\n|-\n|Elephant || [[Rook (chess)|rook]] || \u0939\u093e\u0925\u0940 ''h\u0101th\u012b'' || \u06c1\u0627\u062a\u06be\u06cc ''h\u0101th\u012b''\n|-\n|Horse || [[Knight (chess)|knight]] || \u0918\u094b\u0921\u093c\u093e ''gho\u1e5b\u0101'' || \u06af\u06be\u0648\u0691\u0627 ''gho\u1e5b\u0101''\n|-\n|Camel || [[Bishop (chess)|bishop]] || \u090a\u0902\u091f ''\u016b\u0303\u1e6d'' || \u0627\u0648\u0646\u0679\u06be ''\u016b\u0303\u1e6d''\n|-\n|Infantryman/Soldier || [[Pawn (chess)|pawn]] || \u092a\u0948\u0926\u0932 ''paidal'' / \u092a\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0926\u093e ''py\u0101d\u0101'' / \u0938\u0948\u0928\u093f\u0915 ''sainik'' || \u067e\u06cc\u0627\u062f\u0627 ''py\u0101d\u0101''\n|}\n==Books to refer on Indian Chess==\n* Bhartiya Shatranj [In Hindi] By Dwarka Prasad Gupta , Published By - Vangmaya Prakashan , Jaipur [ ISBN : 81-89755-26-5]\n==See also==\n* [[Origins of chess]]\n* [[Chaturaji]], four-handed version of chaturanga\n* [[Shatranj]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Chess}}\n[[Category:Games related to chaturanga]]\n[[Category:Chess in India]]\n[[Category:18th century in chess]]\n[[Category:Traditional board games]]\n", "text_old": ":''This article is about regional versions of chess played in India. For ancient Indian chess variants, which are believed to be predecessors of chess by some historians, see [[chaturanga]].''\n\n'''Indian chess''' is the name given to a variation of [[chess]] played in [[India]] in the 18th and 19th centuries.  The more ancient forms are known as [[chaturanga]], and spread to the west via [[Persia]] in the 7th Century. There are several such [[Chess variant|variations]], all quite similar to [[rules of chess|modern rules]], with variants regarding [[castling]], [[promotion (chess)|pawn promotion]], etc. These variants were popular in India until the 1960s. However, even today a mix of Indian method and international are used in some parts of India.\n\n== Differences from Western chess ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Expand section|date=July 2010}}\n\n* The [[king (chess)|king]] is always placed to the right of the [[queen (chess)|queen]] (as opposed to the left for Black).\n* King cannot move unless a check is given at least once. \n* When only the king and [[pawn (chess)|pawns]] are left in play, the opponent may not give check, but they can win by stalemate, variants of this include the check being allowed but the capture of last pawn being disallowed (resulting in a draw).\n* The two-step initial pawn move is absent in Indian chess; thus, ''[[en passant]]'' is also absent.\n* Normal castling with rook and king is absent. The king can make a [[knight (chess)|knight's]] move once in a game, known as ''Indian castling''.\n* On reaching the opposite end of the board, pawns [[Promotion (chess)|promote]] to the piece of that square. If it promotes at the initial [[king (chess)|king's]] position, it promotes a [[queen (chess)|queen]].  \n* [[Underpromotion]] is not permitted.\n* The last piece remaining may not be captured, variants include the capture being allowed if the last piece is not a pawn.\n\n==Names of the pieces==\n\nThe following table describes one version of Subcontinental chess terminology for the various pieces (including Hindi and Urdu pronunciations):<ref name=JLC>{{cite web|last1=Cazaux|first1=Jean-Louis|title=Indian Chess Sets|url=http://history.chess.free.fr/india.htm|website=Another view on Chess:  Odyssey of Chess|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! Piece\n!Standard (English)\n! Hindi\n!Urdu\n\n|-\n|King || [[King (chess)|king]] || \u0930\u093e\u091c\u093e ''r\u0101j\u0101'' || \u0628\u0627\u062f\u0634\u0627\u06c1 ''b\u0101dsh\u0101h\n|-\n|Mantri/Vizier/Queen/Senapati || [[Queen (chess)|queen]] || \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 ''mantri'' / \u0935\u091c\u093c\u0940\u0930 ''vaz\u012br'' / \u0930\u093e\u0928\u0940 ''r\u0101n\u012b'' / \u0938\u0947\u0928\u093e\u092a\u0924\u093f ''senapati''||\u0648\u0632\u06cc\u0631\u200e ''vaz\u012br'' / \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u0627 ''malka''\n|-\n|Elephant || [[Rook (chess)|rook]] || \u0939\u093e\u0925\u0940 ''h\u0101th\u012b'' || \u06c1\u0627\u062a\u06be\u06cc ''h\u0101th\u012b''\n|-\n|Horse || [[Knight (chess)|knight]] || \u0918\u094b\u0921\u093c\u093e ''gho\u1e5b\u0101'' || \u06af\u06be\u0648\u0691\u0627 ''gho\u1e5b\u0101''\n|-\n|Camel || [[Bishop (chess)|bishop]] || \u090a\u0902\u091f ''\u016b\u0303\u1e6d'' || \u0627\u0648\u0646\u0679\u06be ''\u016b\u0303\u1e6d''\n|-\n|Infantryman/Soldier || [[Pawn (chess)|pawn]] || \u092a\u0948\u0926\u0932 ''paidal'' / \u092a\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0926\u093e ''py\u0101d\u0101'' / \u0938\u0948\u0928\u093f\u0915 ''sainik'' || \u067e\u06cc\u0627\u062f\u0627 ''py\u0101d\u0101''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Origins of chess]]\n* [[Chaturaji]], four-handed version of chaturanga\n* [[Shatranj]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Chess}}\n[[Category:Games related to chaturanga]]\n[[Category:Chess in India